","1197":"1197","1241":"1241","1192":"1192","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Rhos, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Rhos, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1225–":"1225–Overleden","1192–1241":"1192–1241","1197–Male":"1197–Overleden","1200–1298":"1200–1298","1225–Female":"1225–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","–Unknown":"Overleden","1220–Male":"1220–Overleden","1263–Female":"1263–Overleden","1165–1204":"1165–1204","1178–Female":"1178–Overleden","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1298":"1298","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1263":"1263","1197":"1197","1241":"1241","1192":"1192","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rhos, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Rhos, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1225–":"1225–Deceased","1192–1241":"1192–1241","1197–Male":"1197–Deceased","1200–1298":"1200–1298","1225–Female":"1225–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Unknown":"Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1263–Female":"1263–Deceased","1165–1204":"1165–1204","1178–Female":"1178–Deceased","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1298":"1298","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1263":"1263","1197":"1197","1241":"1241","1192":"1192","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Rhos, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Rhos, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["German: occupational name for a ferryman, Middle High German <i>verje</i>, <i>verge</i>."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sais","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Fernando, Orlando, Angelita, Arturo, Delfina, Desiderio, Dionicio, Edgardo, Elva, Fidel, Isidoro, Jere.","Catalan: topographic name from <i>saix</i> ‘rock’ (from Latin <i>saxum</i>), or an ethnic name for a Saxon, derived from the root of <i>saxó</i> ‘Saxon’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Angharad","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old Celtic intensive prefix <i>an-</i> + <i>cār</i> ‘love’ + the noun suffix <i>-ad</i>. This was the name of the mother of the 12th-century chronicler  Giraldus Cambrensis  (‘Gerald the Welshman’). In the <i>Mabinogi</i>, Angharad Golden Hand at first rejects Peredur's suit, but later falls in love with him when he comes back as the unknown Mute Knight. The name has been strongly revived in Wales since the 1940s, borne, for example, by the actress  Angharad Rees  (  1949-2012 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Angharad ferch Hywel Sais was born in 1225, in Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Hywel Sais ap Rhys - 12, Lord of Deheubarth, was 61 and her mother, Sara le Sore, was 47. She had at least 1 daughter with Gwalter Hen ap Maredudd."},"et":{"1225–":"1225–Surnud","1192–1241":"1192–1241","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1200–1298":"1200–1298","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Unknown":"Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1263–Female":"1263–Surnud","1165–1204":"1165–1204","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1298":"1298","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1263":"1263","1197":"1197","1241":"1241","1192":"1192","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom"